#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h1>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:160
msgid "<span>1. </span>How SQLite Stores Numbers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:163
msgid ""
"SQLite stores integer values in the 64-bit <a "
"href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Two%27s_complement\">twos-complement</a> "
"format&sup1.  This gives a storage range of -9223372036854775808 to "
"+9223372036854775807, inclusive.  Integers within this range are exact."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:170
msgid ""
"So-called \"REAL\" or floating point values are stored in the <a "
"href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_754\">IEEE 754</a> <a "
"href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-precision_floating-point_format\">Binary-64</a> "
"format&sup1.  This gives a range of positive values between approximately "
"1.7976931348623157e+308 and 4.9406564584124654e-324 with an equivalent range "
"of negative values.  A binary64 can also be 0.0 (and -0.0), positive and "
"negative infinity and \"NaN\" or \"Not-a-Number\".  Floating point values "
"are approximate."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:181
msgid "Pay close attention to the last sentence in the previous paragraph:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:182 sedout/floatingpoint.html:291
msgid "<b> Floating point values are approximate.  </b>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:187
msgid ""
"If you need an exact answer, you should not use binary64 floating-point "
"values, in SQLite or in any other product.  This is not an SQLite "
"limitation.  It is a mathematical limitation inherent in the design of "
"floating-point numbers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:191
msgid "&mdash;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p><br>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:191
msgid ""
"&sup1; Exception: The <a href=\"rtree.html\">R-Tree extension</a> stores "
"information as 32-bit floating point or integer values."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h2>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:195
msgid "<span>1.1. </span>Floating-Point Accuracy"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:198
msgid ""
"SQLite promises to preserve the 15 most significant digits of a floating "
"point value.  However, it makes no guarantees about the accuracy of "
"computations on floating point values, as no such guarantees are possible.  "
"Performing math on floating-point values introduces error.  For example, "
"consider what happens if you attempt to subtract two floating-point numbers "
"of similar magnitude:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote><table><tr><td>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:207
msgid "1152693165.1106291898"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote><table><tr><td>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:208
msgid "-1152693165.1106280772"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote><table><tr><td>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:210
msgid "0.0000011126"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:214
msgid ""
"The result shown above (0.0000011126) is the correct answer.  But if you do "
"this computation using binary64 floating-point, the answer you get is "
"0.00000095367431640625 - an error of about 14%.  If you do many similar "
"computations as part of your program, the errors add up so that your final "
"result might be completely meaningless."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:220
msgid ""
"The error arises because only about the first 15 significant digits of each "
"number are stored accurately, and the first difference between the two "
"numbers being subtracted is in the 16th digit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h2>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:224
msgid "<span>1.2. </span>Floating Point Numbers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:227
msgid ""
"The binary64 floating-point format uses 64 bits per number.  Hence there are "
"1.845e+19 different possible floating point values.  On the other hand there "
"are infinitely many real numbers in the range of 1.7977e+308 and "
"4.9407e-324.  It follows then that binary64 cannot possibly represent all "
"possible real numbers within that range.  Approximations are required."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:235
msgid "An IEEE 754 floating-point value is an integer multiplied by a power of two:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:239
msgid "<big>M &times 2<sup><small>E</small></sup></big>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:242
msgid ""
"The M value is the \"mantissa\" and E is the \"exponent\".  Both M and E are "
"integers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:245
msgid ""
"For Binary64, M is a 53-bit integer and E is an 11-bit integer that is "
"offset so that represents a range of values between -1074 and +972, "
"inclusive."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:248
msgid ""
"<i>(NB: The usual description of IEEE 754 is more complex, and it is "
"important to understand the added complexity if you really want to "
"appreciate the details, merits, and limitations of IEEE 754.  However, the "
"integer description shown here, while not exactly right, is easier to "
"understand and is sufficient for the purposes of this article.)</i>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h3>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:254
msgid "<span>1.2.1. </span>Unrepresentable numbers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:256
msgid ""
"Not every decimal number with fewer than 16 significant digits can be "
"represented exactly as a binary64 number.  In fact, most decimal numbers "
"with digits to the right of the decimal point lack an exact binary64 "
"equivalent.  For example, if you have a database column that is intended to "
"hold an item price in dollars and cents, the only cents value that can be "
"exactly represented are 0.00, 0.25, 0.50, and 0.75.  Any other numbers to "
"the right of the decimal point result in an approximation.  If you provide a "
"\"price\" value of 47.49, that number will be represented in binary64 as:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:267
msgid "6683623321994527 &times; 2<sup><small>-47</small></sup>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:270
msgid "Which works out to be:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:273
msgid "47.49000000000000198951966012828052043914794921875"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:276
msgid ""
"That number is very close to 47.49, but it is not exact.  It is a little too "
"big.  If we reduce M by one to 6683623321994526 so that we have the next "
"smaller possible binary64 value, we get:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:281
msgid "47.4899999999999948840923025272786617279052734375"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:286
msgid ""
"This second number is too small.  The first number is closer to the desired "
"value of 47.49, so that is the one that gets used.  But it is not exact.  "
"Most decimal values work this way in IEEE 754.  Remember the key point we "
"made above:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:295
msgid ""
"If you remember nothing else about floating-point values, please don't "
"forget this one key idea."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h3>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:298
msgid "<span>1.2.2. </span>Is it close enough?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:300
msgid ""
"The precision provided by IEEE 754 Binary64 is sufficient for most "
"computations.  For example, if \"47.49\" represents a price and inflation is "
"running at 2% per year, then the price is going up by about 0.0000000301 "
"dollars per second.  The error in the recorded value of 47.49 represents "
"about 66 nanoseconds worth of inflation.  So if the 47.49 price is exact "
"when you enter it, then the effects of inflation will cause the true value "
"to exactly equal the value actually stored "
"(47.4900000000000019895196601282805204391479492187) in less than one "
"ten-millionth of a second.  Surely that level of precision is sufficient for "
"most purposes?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h1>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:311
msgid "<span>2. </span>Extensions For Dealing With Floating Point Numbers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:313
msgid "<a name=\"ieee754ext\"></a>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h2>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:315
msgid "<span>2.1. </span>The ieee754.c Extension"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:317
msgid ""
"The ieee754 extension converts a floating point number between its binary64 "
"representation and the M&times;2<sup><small>E</small></sup> format.  In "
"other words in the expression:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:322
msgid "<big>F = M &times 2<sup><small>E</small></sup></big>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:325
msgid "The ieee754 extension converts between F and (M,E) and back again."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:327
msgid ""
"The ieee754 extension is not part of the <a "
"href=\"amalgamation.html\">amalgamation</a>, but it is included by default "
"in the <a href=\"cli.html\">CLI</a>.  If you want to include the ieee754 "
"extension in your application, you will need to compile and load it "
"separately.  <a name=\"ieee754\"></a>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h3>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:333
msgid "<span>2.1.1. </span>The ieee754() function"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:335
msgid ""
"The ieee754(F) SQL function takes a single floating-point argument as its "
"input and returns a string that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><blockquote>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:339
msgid "'ieee754(M,E)'"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:342
msgid ""
"Except that the M and E are replaced by the mantissa and exponent of the "
"floating point number.  For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><div><pre>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:345
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sqlite> .mode box\n"
"sqlite> SELECT ieee754(47.49) AS x;\n"
"┌───────────────────────────────┐\n"
"│               x               │\n"
"├───────────────────────────────┤\n"
"│ ieee754(6683623321994527,-47) │\n"
"└───────────────────────────────┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:355
msgid ""
"Going in the other direction, the 2-argument version of ieee754() takes the "
"M and E values and converts them into the corresponding F value:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><div><pre>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:358
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sqlite> select ieee754(6683623321994527,-47) as x;\n"
"┌───────┐\n"
"│   x   │\n"
"├───────┤\n"
"│ 47.49 │\n"
"└───────┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:366
msgid "<a name=\"ieee754m\"></a>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h3>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:368
msgid "<span>2.1.2. </span>The ieee754_mantissa() and ieee754_exponent() functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:370
msgid ""
"The text output of the one-argument form of ieee754() is great for human "
"readability, but it is awkward to use as part of a larger expression.  Hence "
"the ieee754_mantissa() and ieee754_exponent() routines were added to return "
"the M and E values corresponding to their single argument F value.  For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><div><pre>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:377
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sqlite> .mode box\n"
"sqlite> SELECT ieee754_mantissa(47.49) AS M, ieee754_exponent(47.49) AS E;\n"
"┌──────────────────┬─────┐\n"
"│        M         │  E  │\n"
"├──────────────────┼─────┤\n"
"│ 6683623321994527 │ -47 │\n"
"└──────────────────┴─────┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:386
msgid "<a name=\"ieee754b\"></a>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><h3>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:388
msgid "<span>2.1.3. </span>The ieee754_from_blob() and ieee754_to_blob() functions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:390
msgid ""
"The ieee754_to_blob(F) SQL function converts the floating point number F "
"into an 8-byte BLOB that is the big-endian binary64 encoding of that "
"number.  The ieee754_from_blob(B) function goes the other way, converting an "
"8-byte blob into the floating-point value that the binary64 encoding "
"represents."
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:395
msgid ""
"So, for example, if you read <a "
"href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double-precision_floating-point_format\">on "
"Wikipedia</a> that the encoding for the minimum positive binary64 value is "
"0x0000000000000001, then you can find the corresponding floating point value "
"like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><div><pre>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:401
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sqlite> .mode box\n"
"sqlite> SELECT ieee754_from_blob(x'0000000000000001') AS F;\n"
"┌───────────────────────┐\n"
"│           F           │\n"
"├───────────────────────┤\n"
"│ 4.94065645841247e-324 │\n"
"└───────────────────────┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><p>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:410
msgid "Or go the other way:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <html><body><div><div><pre>
#: sedout/floatingpoint.html:412
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sqlite> .mode box\n"
"sqlite> SELECT quote(ieee754_to_blob(4.94065645841247e-324)) AS binary64;\n"
"┌─────────────────────┐\n"
"│      binary64       │\n"
"├─────────────────────┤\n"
"│ X'0000000000000001' │\n"
"└─────────────────────┘\n"
msgstr ""

